 to 10 cm−3, the upper limit implied by the plasma wave data. The quiet events gave Ap < 0.2β‖p−0.5. At noon, the unstable component has T⊥p ∼ 20 keV and Ap ∼0.8. At dawn the unstable component has T⊥p ∼ 4 keV and Ap ∼ 2.3. Observed wave frequencies agree with the frequencies of positive growth, and the difference in frequency between noon and dawn is attributable to the combined effects of the different hot proton T⊥p and Ap and the inferred higher cold plasma density at noon. The dawn events had significant growth for highly oblique waves, suggesting that the linear polarization of the dawn waves may be due to domination of the wave spectrum by waves generated with oblique wave vectors.},
   author = {B J Anderson and R E Denton and G Ho and D C Hamilton and S A Fuselier and R J Strangeway},
